{"title_page": "Nick Baines (bishop)", "text_new": "{{short description|British Anglican bishop|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Reverend]]\n| name = Nick Baines\n| title = [[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]]\n| image = Official portrait of The Lord Bishop of Leeds crop 2, 2019.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = The Lord Bishop of Leeds, 2019\n| signature = Signature Nick Baines Bishop Leeds.jpg\n| church = [[Church of England]]\n| diocese = [[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Diocese of Leeds]]\n| term = 8 June 2014{{snd}}present\n| predecessor = ''New see''\n| other_post = area [[Bishop of Croydon]] {{nowrap|(2003\u20132011)}}<br />[[Bishop of Bradford (diocese)|Bishop of Bradford]] {{nowrap|(2011\u20132014)}}<br />Acting Bishop of Leeds {{nowrap|(22 April}}{{snd}}{{nowrap|8 June 2014)}}\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination = 1987 (deacon) <br /> by [[George Hacker (bishop)|George Hacker]] <br /> 1988 (priest) <br /> by [[David Halsey]]\n| consecration = 8 May 2003\n| consecrated_by = [[Rowan Williams]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|11|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]],<!--as was--> {{nowrap|United Kingdom}}\n| nationality = British\n|residence={{nowrap|Hollin House,}} {{nowrap|[[Far Headingley]],}} [[Leeds]]\n| religion = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Linda|1980}}\n| children = three\n| profession = formerly [[linguist]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Bradford]]\n}}\n'''Nicholas''' \"'''Nick'''\" '''Baines''' (born 13 November 1957) is a British [[Anglican]] bishop. He has been the [[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]] since 8 June 2014.<ref name=\"leeds10\">[http://www.gov.uk/government/news/diocese-of-leeds-the-right-reverend-nicholas-baines-approved Number 10 \u2013 Diocese of Leeds: the Right Reverend Nicholas Baines approved] (Accessed 4 February 2014)</ref> He is a former [[Bishop of Bradford (diocese)|Bishop of Bradford]], the [[diocesan bishop]] of the [[Anglican]] [[Diocese of Bradford]] (from 1 April 2011 until 20 April 2014).\n\n==Early life==\nBaines was educated at Holt Comprehensive School, [[South Liverpool]], before gaining a [[Bachelor of Arts]] honours degree (BAHons) in German and French at the [[University of Bradford]]. He worked as a linguist at [[GCHQ]] for four years<ref>\"Hungry for Hope\". See extract at [http://www.churchofscotland.org.uk/shop/catalog/product_info.php?cPath=34&products_id=177 Church of Scotland bookshop] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105101659/http://www.churchofscotland.org.uk/shop/catalog/product_info.php?cPath=34&products_id=177 |date=2009-01-05 }}</ref> prior to training for ordination at [[Trinity College, Bristol]], where he gained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[honours degree]] {BA(Hons)} in theological studies.<ref name=\"prc\">{{cite web|title=New Bishop of Croydon|url=http://www.southwark.anglican.org/news/pr222.htm|website=[[Anglican Diocese of Southwark|Diocese of Southwark]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041030112722/http://www.southwark.anglican.org/news/pr222.htm|archivedate=30 October 2004}}\n</ref>\n\n==Ordained ministry==\nBaines was made a deacon at [[Petertide]] 1987 (5 July) by [[George Hacker (bishop)|George Hacker]], [[Bishop of Penrith]],<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations | archive = 1987_07_10_015 | issue = 6491 | date = 10 July 1987 | page = 15 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> and ordained a priest the Petertide following (3 July 1988) by [[David Halsey]], [[Bishop of Carlisle]], both times at [[Carlisle Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations | archive = 1988_07_08_013 | issue = 6543 | date = 8 July 1988 | page = 13 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> His first appointments were as assistant curate at [[St Thomas' Church, Kendal]] and St Catherine's [[Crook, Cumbria|Crook]].<ref>{{Crockford | forenames = Nicholas | surname = Baines | id = 24431 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> He then moved to [[Leicester]], becoming briefly associate minister of [[Holy Trinity Church, Leicester|Holy Trinity, Leicester]], and then [[Vicar]] of [[Rothley, Leicestershire|Rothley]] (1992-2000), during which time he was also chaplain to an adult mental health unit, before becoming Rural Dean of Goscote in 1995.<ref name=\"prc\" /> In 2000, Baines became the [[Archdeacon of Lambeth]] in the Diocese of Southwark.<ref>{{Who's Who | surname = Baines | othernames = Nicholas | id = U6192 | volume = 2017 | edition = November 2016 online | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> He also oversaw the diocese's children and youth policies and was a member of the [[General Synod of the Church of England]] from 1995 until 2005.\n\n===Episcopal ministry===\nBaines was then appointed [[area bishop|area]] Bishop of Croydon in 2003, succeeding [[Wilfred Wood (bishop)|Wilfred Wood]]. He was [[consecrated]] by [[Rowan Williams]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], at [[St Paul's Cathedral]] and installed in [[Southwark Cathedral]] on 8 May 2003.<ref name=\"prc\" />\n\nThe [[confirmation of election|confirmation]] of Baines' election to the see of Bradford was on 1 April 2011<ref>[http://www.archbishopofyork.org/articles.php/976/new-bishop-for-bradford-diocese Archbishop of York \u2013 New Bishop for Bradford Diocese] (Accessed 11 April 2014)</ref> and he was enthroned at [[Bradford Cathedral]] on 21 May 2011.<ref name=\"bd1\">{{cite web|title=Enthronement of Bishop Nick|website=[[Diocese of Bradford]]|url=http://bradford.anglican.org/bishopscroft/index.php?PageID=enthronement|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108060346/http://bradford.anglican.org/bishopscroft/index.php?PageID=enthronement|archivedate=8 November 2011}}</ref> On 29 May 2013, he consecrated [[Nick Dill]] as [[Bishop of Bermuda]] on behalf of [[Justin Welby]], Archbishop of Canterbury.<ref>[http://www.anglican.ink/article/extra-provincial-dioceses-under-jurisdiction-archbishop-canterbury Anglican Ink \u2014 Extra-Provincial Dioceses under the jurisdiction of the Archbishop of Canterbury] (Accessed 31 January 2016)</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2014, it was announced that Baines would become the diocesan and area [[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]]<ref name=\"leeds10\" /> upon the [[Confirmation of bishops|confirmation of his election]] on 8 June;<ref name=\"baines-wyad\">{{cite web|title=Bishop of Bradford Announced as First Bishop of Leeds for the new Diocese|url=http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content/bishop-bradford-announced-first-bishop-leeds-new-diocese|website=The Transformation Programme for The Diocese of West Yorkshire and the Dales|publisher=[[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Diocese of Leeds]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222200029/http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content%2Fbishop-bradford-announced-first-bishop-leeds-new-diocese|archivedate=22 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> he was acting diocesan and area bishop from 22 April 2014<ref name=\"leeds85\">{{cite web|title=First new diocese for more than 85 years created on April 20|url=http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content/first-new-diocese-more-85-years-created-april-20|website=The Transformation Programme for The Diocese of West Yorkshire and the Dales|publisher=[[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Diocese of Leeds]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420040111/http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content%2Ffirst-new-diocese-more-85-years-created-april-20|archivedate=20 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> (he was licensed as an [[honorary assistant bishop]] of the [[Diocese of York]] to facilitate the acting role.)<ref name=\"rebirth\">{{Church Times | title = Yorkshire dioceses will celebrate Paschal rebirth | url = https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2014/17-april/news/uk/yorkshire-dioceses-will-celebrate-paschal-rebirth | issue = 7883 | date = 17 April 2014 | page = 7 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn 2014 he took his seat in the House of Lords as one of the Lords Spiritual. \n\nBaines is an experienced broadcaster, regularly appearing on ''Pause for Thought'' on [[BBC Radio 2]]. While in Leicester he used to broadcast regularly on [[BBC Radio Leicester]] and [[Leicester Sound]] and twice received a commendation in the Andrew Cross Awards for religious broadcasting.\n\n==Personal life==\nBaines married his wife, Linda, in 1980, and they have three children.\n\n==Selected works==\n\n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Hungry for Hope |date=1991 |publisher=Darton, Longman and Todd |location=London |isbn=978-0232519235 |edition=1st}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Speedbumps and Potholes: Looking for Signs of God in the Everyday |date=2004 |publisher=Saint Andrews Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208069}} \n** ''Am Rande bemerkt'' (German edition)\n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Jesus and People Like Us: The Transforming Power of Grace |date=2004 |publisher=Saint Andrew Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208205}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Marking Time: 47 Reflections on Mark's Gospel for Lent, Holy Week and Easter |date=2005 |publisher=Saint Andrew |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208298}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Hungry for Hope? |date=2007 |publisher=Saint Andrews Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208441 |edition=2nd}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Finding Faith: Stories of Music and Life: Getting in Tune with God |date=2008 |publisher=Saint Andrew |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208687}}\n** ''In hoechsten Toenen'' (German edition)\n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Scandal of Grace: the danger of following Jesus |date=2008 |publisher=Saint Andrew Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208663}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Why Wish You a Merry Christmas?: What Matters (and What Doesn't) in the Festive Season |date=2009 |publisher=Church House Publishing |location=London |isbn=978-0956282101}}\n\n==Styles==\n*''[[The Reverend]]'' Nick Baines (1987\u20132000)\n*''The [[Venerable]]'' Nick Baines (2000\u20132003)\n*''The [[Right Reverend]]'' Nick Baines (2003\u2013present)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|en}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dick Bird]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Archdeacon of Lambeth]]|years=2000\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Skilton]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Wilfred Wood (bishop)|Wilfred Wood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Croydon]]|years=2003\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonathan Clark (bishop)|Jonathan Clark]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David James (bishop)|David James]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Bradford (diocese)|Bishop of Bradford]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-non|reason=''diocese dissolved''}}\n{{s-new|See}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]]|years=8 June 2014{{snd}}present<br />''(Acting 22 April{{snd}}8 June 2014)''}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Archdeacons of Lambeth}}\n{{Bishops of Croydon}}\n{{Bishops of Bradford (diocese)}}\n{{Bishops of Leeds}}\n{{Diocese of Leeds}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baines, Nicholas}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Croydon]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Bradford (diocese)]]\n[[Category:Lords Spiritual]]\n[[Category:Anglican Bishops of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Anglican Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Government Communications Headquarters people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Anglican bishop|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Reverend]]\n| name = Nick Baines\n| title = [[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]]\n| image = Official portrait of The Lord Bishop of Leeds crop 2, 2019.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = The Lord Bishop of Leeds, 2019\n| signature = Signature Nick Baines Bishop Leeds.jpg\n| church = [[Church of England]]\n| diocese = [[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Diocese of Leeds]]\n| term = 8 June 2014{{snd}}present\n| predecessor = ''New see''\n| other_post = area [[Bishop of Croydon]] {{nowrap|(2003\u20132011)}}<br />[[Bishop of Bradford (diocese)|Bishop of Bradford]] {{nowrap|(2011\u20132014)}}<br />Acting Bishop of Leeds {{nowrap|(22 April}}{{snd}}{{nowrap|8 June 2014)}}\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination = 1987 (deacon) <br /> by [[George Hacker (bishop)|George Hacker]] <br /> 1988 (priest) <br /> by [[David Halsey]]\n| consecration = 8 May 2003\n| consecrated_by = [[Rowan Williams]]\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|11|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]],<!--as was--> {{nowrap|United Kingdom}}\n| nationality = British\n|residence={{nowrap|Hollin House,}} {{nowrap|[[Far Headingley]],}} [[Leeds]]\n| religion = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Linda|1980}}\n| children = three\n| profession = formerly [[linguist]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Bradford]]\n}}\n'''Nicholas''' \"'''Nick'''\" '''Baines''' (born 13 November 1957) is a British [[Anglican]] bishop. He has been the [[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]] since 8 June 2014.<ref name=\"leeds10\">[http://www.gov.uk/government/news/diocese-of-leeds-the-right-reverend-nicholas-baines-approved Number 10 \u2013 Diocese of Leeds: the Right Reverend Nicholas Baines approved] (Accessed 4 February 2014)</ref> He is a former [[Bishop of Bradford (diocese)|Bishop of Bradford]], the [[diocesan bishop]] of the [[Anglican]] [[Diocese of Bradford]] (from 1 April 2011 until 20 April 2014).\n\n==Early life==\nBaines was educated at Holt Comprehensive School, [[South Liverpool]], before gaining a [[Bachelor of Arts]] honours degree (BAHons) in German and French at the [[University of Bradford]]. He worked as a linguist at [[GCHQ]] for four years<ref>\"Hungry for Hope\". See extract at [http://www.churchofscotland.org.uk/shop/catalog/product_info.php?cPath=34&products_id=177 Church of Scotland bookshop] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105101659/http://www.churchofscotland.org.uk/shop/catalog/product_info.php?cPath=34&products_id=177 |date=2009-01-05 }}</ref> prior to training for ordination at [[Trinity College, Bristol]], where he gained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[honours degree]] {BA(Hons)} in theological studies.<ref name=\"prc\">{{cite web|title=New Bishop of Croydon|url=http://www.southwark.anglican.org/news/pr222.htm|website=[[Anglican Diocese of Southwark|Diocese of Southwark]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041030112722/http://www.southwark.anglican.org/news/pr222.htm|archivedate=30 October 2004}}\n</ref>\n\n==Ordained ministry==\nBaines was made a deacon at [[Petertide]] 1987 (5 July) by [[George Hacker (bishop)|George Hacker]], [[Bishop of Penrith]],<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations | archive = 1987_07_10_015 | issue = 6491 | date = 10 July 1987 | page = 15 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> and ordained a priest the Petertide following (3 July 1988) by [[David Halsey]], [[Bishop of Carlisle]], both times at [[Carlisle Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations | archive = 1988_07_08_013 | issue = 6543 | date = 8 July 1988 | page = 13 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> His first appointments were as assistant curate at [[St Thomas' Church, Kendal]] and St Catherine's [[Crook, Cumbria|Crook]].<ref>{{Crockford | forenames = Nicholas | surname = Baines | id = 24431 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> He then moved to [[Leicester]], becoming briefly associate minister of [[Holy Trinity Church, Leicester|Holy Trinity, Leicester]], and then [[Vicar]] of [[Rothley, Leicestershire|Rothley]] (1992-2000), during which time he was also chaplain to an adult mental health unit, before becoming Rural Dean of Goscote in 1995.<ref name=\"prc\" /> In 2000, Baines became the [[Archdeacon of Lambeth]] in the Diocese of Southwark.<ref>{{Who's Who | surname = Baines | othernames = Nicholas | id = U6192 | volume = 2017 | edition = November 2016 online | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref> He also oversaw the diocese's children and youth policies and was a member of the [[General Synod of the Church of England]] from 1995 until 2005.\n\n===Episcopal ministry===\nBaines was then appointed [[area bishop|area]] Bishop of Croydon in 2003, succeeding [[Wilfred Wood (bishop)|Wilfred Wood]]. He was [[consecrated]] by [[Rowan Williams]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], at [[St Paul's Cathedral]] and installed in [[Southwark Cathedral]] on 8 May 2003.<ref name=\"prc\" />\n\nThe [[confirmation of election|confirmation]] of Baines' election to the see of Bradford was on 1 April 2011<ref>[http://www.archbishopofyork.org/articles.php/976/new-bishop-for-bradford-diocese Archbishop of York \u2013 New Bishop for Bradford Diocese] (Accessed 11 April 2014)</ref> and he was enthroned at [[Bradford Cathedral]] on 21 May 2011.<ref name=\"bd1\">{{cite web|title=Enthronement of Bishop Nick|website=[[Diocese of Bradford]]|url=http://bradford.anglican.org/bishopscroft/index.php?PageID=enthronement|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108060346/http://bradford.anglican.org/bishopscroft/index.php?PageID=enthronement|archivedate=8 November 2011}}</ref> On 29 May 2013, he consecrated [[Nick Dill]] as [[Bishop of Bermuda]] on behalf of [[Justin Welby]], Archbishop of Canterbury.<ref>[http://www.anglican.ink/article/extra-provincial-dioceses-under-jurisdiction-archbishop-canterbury Anglican Ink \u2014 Extra-Provincial Dioceses under the jurisdiction of the Archbishop of Canterbury] (Accessed 31 January 2016)</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2014, it was announced that Baines would become the diocesan and area [[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]]<ref name=\"leeds10\" /> upon the [[Confirmation of bishops|confirmation of his election]] on 8 June;<ref name=\"baines-wyad\">{{cite web|title=Bishop of Bradford Announced as First Bishop of Leeds for the new Diocese|url=http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content/bishop-bradford-announced-first-bishop-leeds-new-diocese|website=The Transformation Programme for The Diocese of West Yorkshire and the Dales|publisher=[[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Diocese of Leeds]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222200029/http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content%2Fbishop-bradford-announced-first-bishop-leeds-new-diocese|archivedate=22 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> he was acting diocesan and area bishop from 22 April 2014<ref name=\"leeds85\">{{cite web|title=First new diocese for more than 85 years created on April 20|url=http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content/first-new-diocese-more-85-years-created-april-20|website=The Transformation Programme for The Diocese of West Yorkshire and the Dales|publisher=[[Anglican Diocese of Leeds|Diocese of Leeds]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420040111/http://www.wyadtransformation.org/?q=content%2Ffirst-new-diocese-more-85-years-created-april-20|archivedate=20 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> (he was licensed as an [[honorary assistant bishop]] of the [[Diocese of York]] to facilitate the acting role.)<ref name=\"rebirth\">{{Church Times | title = Yorkshire dioceses will celebrate Paschal rebirth | url = https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2014/17-april/news/uk/yorkshire-dioceses-will-celebrate-paschal-rebirth | issue = 7883 | date = 17 April 2014 | page = 7 | accessed = 10 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\nBaines is an experienced broadcaster, regularly appearing on ''Pause for Thought'' on [[BBC Radio 2]]. While in Leicester he used to broadcast regularly on [[BBC Radio Leicester]] and [[Leicester Sound]] and twice received a commendation in the Andrew Cross Awards for religious broadcasting.\n\n==Personal life==\nBaines married his wife, Linda, in 1980, and they have three children.\n\n==Selected works==\n\n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Hungry for Hope |date=1991 |publisher=Darton, Longman and Todd |location=London |isbn=978-0232519235 |edition=1st}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Speedbumps and Potholes: Looking for Signs of God in the Everyday |date=2004 |publisher=Saint Andrews Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208069}} \n** ''Am Rande bemerkt'' (German edition)\n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Jesus and People Like Us: The Transforming Power of Grace |date=2004 |publisher=Saint Andrew Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208205}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Marking Time: 47 Reflections on Mark's Gospel for Lent, Holy Week and Easter |date=2005 |publisher=Saint Andrew |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208298}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Hungry for Hope? |date=2007 |publisher=Saint Andrews Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208441 |edition=2nd}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Finding Faith: Stories of Music and Life: Getting in Tune with God |date=2008 |publisher=Saint Andrew |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208687}}\n** ''In hoechsten Toenen'' (German edition)\n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Scandal of Grace: the danger of following Jesus |date=2008 |publisher=Saint Andrew Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0715208663}} \n* {{cite book |last1=Baines |first1=Nick |title=Why Wish You a Merry Christmas?: What Matters (and What Doesn't) in the Festive Season |date=2009 |publisher=Church House Publishing |location=London |isbn=978-0956282101}}\n\n==Styles==\n*''[[The Reverend]]'' Nick Baines (1987\u20132000)\n*''The [[Venerable]]'' Nick Baines (2000\u20132003)\n*''The [[Right Reverend]]'' Nick Baines (2003\u2013present)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|en}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dick Bird]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Archdeacon of Lambeth]]|years=2000\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chris Skilton]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Wilfred Wood (bishop)|Wilfred Wood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Croydon]]|years=2003\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonathan Clark (bishop)|Jonathan Clark]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David James (bishop)|David James]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Bradford (diocese)|Bishop of Bradford]]|years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-non|reason=''diocese dissolved''}}\n{{s-new|See}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Anglican Bishop of Leeds|Bishop of Leeds]]|years=8 June 2014{{snd}}present<br />''(Acting 22 April{{snd}}8 June 2014)''}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Archdeacons of Lambeth}}\n{{Bishops of Croydon}}\n{{Bishops of Bradford (diocese)}}\n{{Bishops of Leeds}}\n{{Diocese of Leeds}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baines, Nicholas}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Archdeacons of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Croydon]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Bradford (diocese)]]\n[[Category:Lords Spiritual]]\n[[Category:Anglican Bishops of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Anglican Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Government Communications Headquarters people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Exarcu", "label": "safe", "comment": "All", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nick_Baines_(bishop)"}
{"title_page": "Tornadoes of 2020", "text_new": "{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 - ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]]\n|max_date      = March 3\n|tornadoes_usa = 209\n|total_damages_usa = unknown\n|total_fatalities_world = 64\n|total_fatalities_usa = 64\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 245 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which 209 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 64 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 207\n|FU = 6\n|F0 = 66\n|F1 = 99\n|F2 = 33\n|F3 = 3\n|F4 = 1\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 87 were confirmed.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\nA squall line with embedded tornadoes moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes in [[Haughton, Louisiana]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere have been 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 have been confirmed.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\nAcross the three-day outbreak, at least 37 tornadoes were confirmed. One person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> A large, long-tracked EF2 tornado caused extensive damage in rural southeastern Mississippi.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 - 02/06/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> Another EF2 tornado touched down in [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]] just north of Charlotte. No injuries were reported, but there was some property damage and downed power lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> A roof was ripped off of one home.<ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> More tornadoes were confirmed in or near [[Gold Hill, North Carolina|Gold Hill]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref> [[Pineville, North Carolina|Pineville]],<ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and [[Albemarle, North Carolina|Albemarle]] in North Carolina<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]].<ref name=WBTV/> Heavy damage was reported in several towns, including Spartanburg. Along with the tornadic storms, a widespread amount of flooding has also occurred throughout the southern states.\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere have been 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 76 have been confirmed.\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:Putnam County TN tornado damage 2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|A home near Cookeville, destroyed by an EF4 tornado on March 3.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\n[[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a tornado of EF3 strength just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage was reported as the tornado moved through downtown and into [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson County]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. Three tornadoes killed 26 people in [[Benton County, Tennessee|Benton]], [[Davidson County, Tennessee|Davidson]], [[Putnam County, Tennessee|Putnam]] and [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson]] counties, including two in [[East Nashville, Tennessee|East Nashville]]. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled along a narrow path, with several swept clean from their foundations.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2-3, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> A lone [[supercell]] was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nDuring the evenings of March 18 and 19, rounds of severe storms impacted a large area from [[West Texas]] to [[Ohio]], spawning several tornadoes. On March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event - Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Overnight, an EF2 tornado damaged a farm southwest of [[Merkel, Texas]], and another EF2 debarked trees and damaged a home nearby (these two tracks may have been the same tornado).<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce an EF1 and an EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/>\n\nOn March 19, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]], removing the top floor from one house and tossing an exercise bike into the side window of a [[Chevrolet Suburban|Chevy suburban]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes touched down in Arkansas, one of which caused damage between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], destroying one home and tearing the roof off of another.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another in Arkansas.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nAn EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage and causing 22 injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC - 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Damage from Jonesboro shows numerous cars lofted and mangled in a shopping mall parking lot, with missile debris embedded into the ground. A train was also derailed, while the municipal airport sustained major damage, with hangars demolished and at least one plane flipped.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nAn EF2 tornado was on the ground for 17 miles southwest of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying a barn and damaging dozens of homes and outbuildings.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 touched down concurrently in [[Newburgh, Indiana]], removing portions of roofs or walls on five homes and damaging several others. Two people were injured.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, with 15 preliminary tornado reports in the [[southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nAn EF2 tornado caused significant damage in [[Eufaula, Alabama]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> and several weaker ones were reported in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> Another tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 20 tornadoes reported in the United States in April, of which 19 have been confirmed.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 10|EF1= 8|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nSeveral tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8. Later in the afternoon on April 8, an EF0 tornado briefly touched down west-southwest of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]] near the town of [[Cash, Arkansas|Cash]], followed by an EF2 tornado in the vicinity of [[Weiner, Arkansas|Weiner]] and [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged as well.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Numerous homes were heavily damaged and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> More tornadoes, mainly weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio.\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 0|F1 = 2|F2 = 1|F3 = 2|F4 = 0|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\nA moderate risk severe weather outlook was issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]], beginning with the day-3 outlook on April 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/pmarshwx/status/1129744566163333122?s=20|title=Patrick Marsh on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado watch|Tornado Watch]] was issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as a confirmed tornado moved through the city limits causing significant damage to homes, businesses, and the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce a pair of long-tracked tornadoes that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergencies]] for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast [[Mississippi]] and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center - PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a preliminarily-rated [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20|title=NWS Morristown on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nA strengthening [[squall line]] marched its way into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]] in the early morning hours of April 13, where an enhanced risk severe weather outlook had been issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]]. An embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado shortly after the [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] was issued for the city at 6:55 a.m. EDT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 - ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]]\n|max_date      = March 3\n|tornadoes_usa = 209\n|total_damages_usa = unknown\n|total_fatalities_world = 64\n|total_fatalities_usa = 64\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 245 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which 209 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 64 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 207\n|FU = 6\n|F0 = 66\n|F1 = 99\n|F2 = 33\n|F3 = 3\n|F4 = 1\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 87 were confirmed.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\nA squall line with embedded tornadoes moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes in [[Haughton, Louisiana]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere have been 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 have been confirmed.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\nAcross the three-day outbreak, at least 37 tornadoes were confirmed. One person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> A large, long-tracked EF2 tornado caused extensive damage in rural southeastern Mississippi.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 - 02/06/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> Another EF2 tornado touched down in [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]] just north of Charlotte. No injuries were reported, but there was some property damage and downed power lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> A roof was ripped off of one home.<ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> More tornadoes were confirmed in or near [[Gold Hill, North Carolina|Gold Hill]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref> [[Pineville, North Carolina|Pineville]],<ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and [[Albemarle, North Carolina|Albemarle]] in North Carolina<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> and [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]].<ref name=WBTV/> Heavy damage was reported in several towns, including Spartanburg. Along with the tornadic storms, a widespread amount of flooding has also occurred throughout the southern states.\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere have been 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 76 have been confirmed.\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:Putnam County TN tornado damage 2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|A home near Cookeville, destroyed by an EF4 tornado on March 3.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\n[[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a tornado of EF3 strength just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage was reported as the tornado moved through downtown and into [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson County]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. Three tornadoes killed 26 people in [[Benton County, Tennessee|Benton]], [[Davidson County, Tennessee|Davidson]], [[Putnam County, Tennessee|Putnam]] and [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson]] counties, including two in [[East Nashville, Tennessee|East Nashville]]. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled along a narrow path, with several swept clean from their foundations.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2-3, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> A lone [[supercell]] was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nDuring the evenings of March 18 and 19, rounds of severe storms impacted a large area from [[West Texas]] to [[Ohio]], spawning several tornadoes. On March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event - Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Overnight, an EF2 tornado damaged a farm southwest of [[Merkel, Texas]], and another EF2 debarked trees and damaged a home nearby (these two tracks may have been the same tornado).<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce an EF1 and an EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/>\n\nOn March 19, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]], removing the top floor from one house and tossing an exercise bike into the side window of a [[Chevrolet Suburban|Chevy suburban]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes touched down in Arkansas, one of which caused damage between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], destroying one home and tearing the roof off of another.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another in Arkansas.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nAn EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage and causing 22 injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC - 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Damage from Jonesboro shows numerous cars lofted and mangled in a shopping mall parking lot, with missile debris embedded into the ground. A train was also derailed, while the municipal airport sustained major damage, with hangars demolished and at least one plane flipped.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nAn EF2 tornado was on the ground for 17 miles southwest of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying a barn and damaging dozens of homes and outbuildings.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 touched down concurrently in [[Newburgh, Indiana]], removing portions of roofs or walls on five homes and damaging several others. Two people were injured.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, with 15 preliminary tornado reports in the [[southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nAn EF2 tornado caused significant damage in [[Eufaula, Alabama]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> and several weaker ones were reported in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> Another tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 20 tornadoes reported in the United States in April, of which 19 have been confirmed.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 10|EF1= 8|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nSeveral tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8. Later in the afternoon on April 8, an EF0 tornado briefly touched down west-southwest of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]] near the town of [[Cash, Arkansas|Cash]], followed by an EF2 tornado in the vicinity of [[Weiner, Arkansas|Weiner]] and [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged as well.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Numerous homes were heavily damaged and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> More tornadoes, mainly weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio.\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 0|F1 = 2|F2 = 1|F3 = 1|F4 = 0|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\nA moderate risk severe weather outlook was issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]], beginning with the day-3 outlook on April 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/pmarshwx/status/1129744566163333122?s=20|title=Patrick Marsh on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado watch|Tornado Watch]] was issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as a confirmed tornado moved through the city limits causing significant damage to homes, businesses, and the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce a pair of long-tracked tornadoes that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergencies]] for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast [[Mississippi]] and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center - PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a preliminarily-rated [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20|title=NWS Morristown on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nA strengthening [[squall line]] marched its way into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]] in the early morning hours of April 13, where an enhanced risk severe weather outlook had been issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]]. An embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado shortly after the [[Tornado emergency|Tornado Emergency]] was issued for the city at 6:55 a.m. EDT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "name_user": "Alehol", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 12\u201313", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornadoes_of_2020"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Charles", "text_new": "[[Image:Daniel Charles-1992.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Daniel Charles in 1992.]]\n\n'''Daniel Paul Charles''' was a French [[musician]], [[musicologist]] and [[philosopher]]. He was born on 27 November 1935 in [[Oran]] ([[Algeria]]) and died on 21 August 2008 in [[Antibes]] ([[France]]).\n\n== Biography ==\n\nHe was a student of [[Olivier Messiaen]] at the Paris Conservatory of Music (First Prize, 1956), he received the aggregation in philosophy in 1959 and a PhD under the direction of [[Mikel Dufrenne]] in 1977.\n\nAfter leading (late 1968) the Commission charged with establishing the status of professorship of music at the French Ministry of Education, he founded and lead for twenty years (1969\u20131989) the Department of Music of [[University of Paris VIII]] (Vincennes, and St. Denis). He was also responsible, from 1970 to 1980, for the teaching of general aesthetics at the [[University of Paris IV]] (Sorbonne). He decided to end his career by teaching philosophy at the [[University of Nice Sophia-Antipolis]] (1989\u20131999).\n\nWhen he graduated from the [[Paris Conservatory of Music]] in 1956, he participated in the [[Groupe de Recherches Musicales|GRM]] under the leadership of [[Pierre Schaeffer]], and proposed to set into electronic music [[St\u00e9phane Mallarm\u00e9]]'s \"[[Un Coup de D\u00e9s Jamais N'Abolira Le Hasard (Mallarm\u00e9)|Coup de d\u00e9s]]\" in [[Darmstadt]], a project which caught the attention of [[Karlheinz Stockhausen]]. But his lack of enthusiasm toward the \"solf\u00e8ge des bruits\" of Schaeffer led him to focus instead on [[John Cage]], whom he met in 1958. He contributed then to present Cage's music and philosophy in France: [[Pour les oiseaux]] (co-signed with Cage), published first in French (Paris, Belfond, 1976) became a classic book. It was later published in English: [[For the Birds (book)|For the Birds]].\n\nDaniel Charles has been invited by many universities to lecture (usually across the Atlantic, but also including Japan and the Philippines), and has published many articles and several books, five of which have been translated into German, and two into Japanese.\n\n== Publications ==\n\n=== Main Publications ===\n* ''Pour les Oiseaux'' (Entretiens avec John Cage), Paris, Pierre Belfond, 1976 / L'Herne, 2002. translated in English, German, Spanish, Italian and Japanese.\n* ''Le Temps de la voix'', Paris, J.-P. Delarge, 1978 / Hermann, 2011.\n* ''Gloses sur Cage'', Paris, U.G.E., Coll. 10/18, 1978 / Descl\u00e9e de Brouwer, 2002.\n* ''John Cage oder Musik ist los'', Berlin, Merve Verlag, 1984.\n* ''Poetik der Gleichzeitigkeit'', Bern, Benteli Verlag, 1987.\n* ''Zeitspielr\u00e4ume'', Berlin, Merve Verlag, 1989.\n* ''Musketaquid, Musik und Transzendentalismus'', Berlin, Merve, 1994.\n* ''Musiques nomades'', Paris, Kim\u00e9, 1998.\n* ''La fiction de la postmodernit\u00e9 selon l'esprit de la musique'', Paris, P.U.F., 2001.\n\n=== Direction of magazines ===\n6 special issues of ''Revue d'Esth\u00e9tique'' (from 1968 to 1998), among them: \"John Cage\" Number 13-14-15 (1989) (Toulouse, Privat / Paris, J.-M. Place).\n\n=== Articles ===\nMore than 200 articles published in several magazines (''Revue musicale, Analyse musicale, VH 101, Traverses, Corps \u00e9crit, Exercices de la patience, Le Temps de la r\u00e9flexion, Etc. Montr\u00e9al, Parachute, Discourse, The Musical Quarterly, The World and I, Alpha-beta, Il Verri, Synteesi, Musik-Konzept''e, etc.), in collective books, and several encyclopedias, prefaces, LPs and CDs booklets, etc.\n\n=== Translations (from English) ===\n* [[Abraham A. Moles]], ''Experimental Music'' (\"Les Musiques exp\u00e9rimentales\", Z\u00fcrich, Cercle d'Art, 1966)\n* [[Alfred North Whitehead]], ''Process and Reality'' (\"Proc\u00e8s et r\u00e9alit\u00e9\", Paris, Gallimard, 1996 - in collaboration with C.R.H.I., [[CNRS]] and [[University of Nice Sophia-Antipolis]]).\n* [[John Cage]], ''Je n'ai jamais \u00e9cout\u00e9 aucun son sans l'aimer: le seul probl\u00e8me avec les sons, c'est la musique'' (La Souterraine, Ed. Pierre Courtaud, Coll. La Main courante, 1994).\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://home.att.ne.jp/grape/charles/dc.html official site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charles, Daniel}}\n[[Category:People from Oran]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century French musicologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French philosophers]]\n[[Category:French male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French musicians]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Daniel Charles-1992.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Daniel Charles in 1992.]]\n\n'''Daniel Paul Charles''' was a French [[musician]], [[musicologist]] and [[philosopher]]. He was born on 27 November 1935 in [[Oran]] ([[Algeria]]) and died on 21 August 2008 in [[Antibes]] ([[France]]).\n\n== Biography ==\n\nHe was a student of [[Olivier Messiaen]] at the Paris Conservatory of Music (First Prize, 1956), he received the aggregation in philosophy in 1959 and a PhD under the direction of [[Mikel Dufrenne]] in 1977.\n\nAfter leading (late 1968) the Commission charged with establishing the status of professorship of music at the French Ministry of Education, he founded and lead for twenty years (1969\u20131989) the Department of Music of [[University of Paris VIII]] (Vincennes, and St. Denis). He was also responsible, from 1970 to 1980, for the teaching of general aesthetics at the [[University of Paris IV]] (Sorbonne). He decided to end his career by teaching philosophy at the [[University of Nice Sophia-Antipolis]] (1989\u20131999).\n\nWhen he graduated from the [[Paris Conservatory of Music]] in 1956, he participated in the [[Groupe de Recherches Musicales|GRM]] under the leadership of [[Pierre Schaeffer]], and proposed to set into electronic music [[St\u00e9phane Mallarm\u00e9]]'s \"[[Un Coup de D\u00e9s Jamais N'Abolira Le Hasard (Mallarm\u00e9)|Coup de d\u